			<ns0:name>mseaborn@chromium.org</ns0:name><ns0:uri>/u/mseaborn@chromium.org/</ns0:uri></ns0:author><ns0:content type="html">I'm not convinced there's a way to test this using the Windows debug API.  The idea was that we could single-step through a fault to see what userland address is executed immediately after the fault.  But the kernel will clear the x86 trap flag before passing control to KiUserExceptionDispatcher, so we can't single-step that part.</ns0:content><ns0:updated>2012-08-10T22:51:05.000Z</ns0:updated><ns0:published>2012-08-10T22:51:05.000Z</ns0:published><ns2:updates>
